The CoV evaluation on phantom data allowed for the isolation of hardware‐related effects from anatomical effects (e.g., surrounding tissue of varying T2 and diversified intrinsic diffusivities or degrees of anisotropy, contributing to varying degree a direction‐dependent signal in the voxels of interest) and confounding motion effects, which complicate the quantitative evaluation of EC‐induced image distortions in vivo. Instead, the observed high values in CoV maps for Ref. EPI can be mostly attributed to incompletely accounted field perturbations and illustrate the minimum level of image distortions anticipated for in vivo acquisitions employing the same diffusion sampling schemes. The discrepancies of the vial boundaries were minimized with the expanded encoding model reconstruction, leading to very low CoV at the edges of the vials – upon visual inspection even lower than obtained with bipolar or eddy current nulled (ENCODE) gradients (Figure 2 in Zhang et al.
